{{hatnote|Not to be confused with the [[Anglo-Saxon Chronicle]] or [[The Saxon Chronicles]].}}

The '''Chronicle of the Saxons''' ({{lang-cy|'''Brut y Saeson'''}}) is a Welsh-language chronicle running from 683 to 1197.<ref>Turner, Sharon. ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=514VAAAAQAAJ&pg=PA228 The history of the Anglo-Saxons from the earliest period to the Norman conquest]'', Vol. 1. Baudry's European Library, 1840. Accessed 19 Feb 2013.</ref> One manuscript attributes it to [[Caradog of Llancarfan]].<ref>Baynes, Thomas (ed.) ''The Encyclopædia Britannica'', Vol. 5. "[https://books.google.com/books?id=HKgMAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA316 Celtic Literature]". Scribner's Sons, 1833. Accessed 19 Feb 2013.</ref> It appears to consist primarily of passages of the [[Chronicle of the Princes]] and the [[Annals of Winchester]], with other minor sources as well.<ref>Lappenberg, J.M. & al. ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=bTfvnU9f8YQC&pg=PR33 A History Of England Under The Anglo-saxon Kings]''. 1845. Accessed 19 Feb 2013.</ref>

