{{italic title}}
{{Orphan|date=December 2013}}

'''''Kaffir Folk-lore: A Selection from the Traditional Tales''''' is a book by [[George McCall Theal]] published in 1886.  It is sometimes called '''''Kaffir (Xhosa) Folk-lore''''' or even '''''Xhosa Folk-lore''''' to avoid the word [[Kaffir (racial term)|kaffir]], which has since become a derogatory term (in the time the book was written, however, it was frequently used to refer to the [[Xhosa people|Xhosa]] people{{Citation needed|date=May 2009}}).

The book contains twenty-three Xhosa [[folklore|folk-tales]] and a list of common [[proverb]]s, all of which were collected from, recorded by, and verified by native Xhosa whom Theal questioned.  It also includes several pages of [[footnotes]] written by Theal himself, mainly translating Xhosa words and explaining parts of Xhosa culture.

