'''Quentin Duane Wheeler''' (born January 31, 1954)<ref>[http://errol.oclc.org/laf/n82-215424.html Library of Congress Authority File.] Accessed: June 4, 2014.</ref> was the [[List of heads of the New York State College of Forestry|fourth]] President of the [[State University of New York College of Environmental Science and Forestry]], in [[Syracuse, New York]]. He is an American [[entomologist]], [[Taxonomy (biology)|taxonomist]], author and [[newspaper columnist]], and is the founding director of the [[International Institute for Species Exploration]]. Previously, he had been professor of entomology at [[Cornell University]] and [[Arizona State University]], and had served as the Keeper and Head of Entomology at the [[Natural History Museum, London|Natural History Museum]] in London, and Director of the Division of Environmental Biology at the [[National Science Foundation]]. In March 2018, he announced his intention to resign from SUNY ESF, effective June 30, 2018.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Mulder|first1=James T.|title=Controversial SUNY ESF president stepping down after feuding with faculty|url=http://www.syracuse.com/schools/index.ssf/2018/03/post_10.html|publisher=Syracuse.com|accessdate=21 March 2018|date=21 March 2018}}</ref>

== Education ==
Wheeler holds bachelor (1976), master's (1977) and Ph.D. (1980) degrees in [[entomology]] from [[Ohio State University]].<ref name=esf>[http://www.esf.edu/communications/view.asp?newsID=2436 "Quentin Wheeler Chosen as New President of SUNY-ESF,"] SUNY-ESF, November 15, 2013. Accessed: February 22, 2014.</ref><ref>[http://sustainability.asu.edu/research/persbio.php?pid=8049 "Quentin Wheeler,"] Global Institute of Sustainability, Arizona State University. Accessed: February 22, 2014.</ref> His Ph.D. dissertation was entitled, ''"Comparative [[morphology (biology)|morphology]], [[cladistics]], and a revised classification of the genera [[Lymexylidae]] ([[beetle|Coleoptera]]), including descriptions of two new genera".''<ref>[https://www.researchgate.net/publication/35857259_Comparative_morphology_cladistics_and_a_revised_classification_of_the_genera_Lymexylidae_%28Coleoptera%29_including_descriptions_of_two_new_genera "Quentin Wheeler,"] ResearchGate. Accessed: February 14, 2014.</ref>

== Career ==

Wheeler was a faculty member for 24 years at [[Cornell University]], where he earned the rank of tenured full professor. He was chair of entomology and director of the Liberty Hyde Bailey [[Herbarium|Hortorium]] at [[Cornell University|Cornell]]. Wheeler also previously served as the Keeper and Head of [[Entomology]] at the [[Natural History Museum, London|Natural History Museum]] in London from 2004–2006, and was director of the Division of [[Environmental Biology]] at the [[National Science Foundation]] from 2001-2004.[[File:Quentin-Wheeler-2009.jpg|thumb|left|Quentin Wheeler, speaking at the annual meeting of the [[History of Science Society]], Phoenix, Arizona, November 2009 (photo by Sage Ross)]]

Wheeler joined [[Arizona State University]] in 2006. He was the Virginia M. Ullman Professor of Natural History and the Environment, and founding executive director of the [[International Institute for Species Exploration]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Jackson|first1=Nicholas|title=A Conversation With Quentin D. Wheeler, Sustainability Scientist|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/national/archive/2011/11/a-conversation-with-quentin-d-wheeler-sustainability-scientist/248376/|work=The Atlantic|accessdate=15 November 2014|date=18 November 2011}}</ref> Wheeler served as interim dean of the Division of Natural Sciences in 2006, and in 2007 was appointed to the position of vice president and dean of the College of Liberal Arts and Sciences, a position he held until 2011. He was President of the [[State University of New York College of Environmental Science and Forestry]] from January 2014 through June 2018.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Tobin|first1=Dave|title=SUNY ESF's next president, Quentin Wheeler, is a bug expert|url=http://www.syracuse.com/news/index.ssf/2013/11/quentin_wheeler_chosen_as_new_president_of_suny-esf.html|website=Syracuse.com|accessdate=15 November 2014|date=15 November 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Willis|first1=Scott|last2=Farrell|first2=Sean|title=Dr. Quentin Wheeler Inaugurated as SUNY ESF's Fourth President|url=http://waer.org/post/dr-quentin-wheeler-inaugurated-suny-esfs-fourth-president|publisher=WAER 795|accessdate=15 November 2014}}</ref><ref>[https://www.syracuse.com/news/index.ssf/2018/06/upstate_medical_vp_to_serve_as_interim_president_of_suny_esf.html Mulder, James T. (2018, June 14). "Upstate Medical VP to serve as interim president of SUNY ESF,"] Syracuse.com. Accessed: 1 July 2018.</ref> In March 2018, he announced his intention to resign from SUNY ESF, effective June 30, 2018.<ref>[https://www.syracuse.com/schools/index.ssf/2018/03/post_10.html Mulder,
James T. (2018, March 21). "Controversial SUNY ESF president stepping down after feuding with faculty,"] Syracuse.com Accessed: 11 September 2018.</ref>

== Research ==

Wheeler's research career has focused on the role of [[species exploration]] and [[natural history]] collections in the exploration and conservation of [[biodiversity]]; theory and practice of [[cladistics|phylogenetic systematics]] and [[cybertaxonomy]]; the evolution and classification of insects, especially [[beetles]]; and public [[science education]]. He has received a number of academic honors, including several fellowships.{{such as?}} He has had three species of beetles named in his honor, such as ''Tonerus wheeleri'',<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Miller|first1=Kelly B.|title=On the systematics of Noteridae (Coleoptera: Adephaga: Hydradephaga): Phylogeny, description of a new tribe, genus and species, and survey of female genital morphology|journal=Systematics and Biodiversity|date=2009|volume=7|issue=2|pages=191–214|doi=10.1017/S1477200008002946}}</ref> ''Eleodes wheeleri'',<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Smith|first1=Aaron|last2=Dornburg|first2=Rebecca|last3=Wheeler|first3=Quentin|title=Larvae of the genus Eleodes (Coleoptera, Tenebrionidae): matrix-based descriptions, cladisticanalysis, and key to late instars|journal=ZooKeys|date=2014|volume=415|pages=217–268|doi=10.3897/zookeys.415.5887|pmid=25009429|pmc=4089825}}</ref> and ''Agathisium wheeleri''.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Angelini|first1=Fernando|title=New Species and Records of Agathidium from Malaysia (Malaya) and the Philippines (Coleoptera: Leiodidae)|journal=The Coleopterists Bulletin|date=1990|volume=44|issue=3|pages=241–254|jstor=4008726}}</ref>

He is the author of approximately 150 scientific articles and six books, including ''What on Earth? – 100 of Our Planet's Most Amazing New Species''. He has named more than 100 new species and writes a periodic column on new species for ''[[The Guardian]]'' newspaper in London.<ref name=esf />

